{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110201/0432.xml":{"full_text":"Editorial Page\nPart 2\u2014B Pages\nPROSPERITY IS DECLARED\nBOUND TO RETURN SOON\nFirestone Says Nation With Sleeves\nRolled Up Is Uncjuestionably\non Uphill Path.\nBY HARVEY S. FIRESTONE.\nIDO not know on what date national\nprosp?rity will return. I cannpt\neven name the month In which\nthere will be such a substantial up\nturn in business throughout the\ncountry that there will be national rec\nognition of the return of \u2018\u2018good times.\u201d\nBut this I do know: That we shall\nhave in America, and beginning reason\nably soon, an era of prosperity for the\nmasses of our people eclipsing anything\nof the kind we have had before.\nI am not saying this with any purpose\nto \u2018\u2018boom business.l know that busi\nness cannot be artificially \u2018\u2018boomed\u201d for\nvery long or very widely. When busi\nness recovery comes, it will come not'\nbecause of any widely advertised \u201cbuy\nmore-for-prosperity\" campaigns, but be-\ncause those who advertise have more\nto offer.\nIn short, business recovery will result\nfrom the natural workings of economic\nlaws\u2014just as a broken leg knits, heals j\nand mends from within, and not because j\nof any ointment or \u201cremedy\" applied by\na physician. There are certain things\nthat can and should be done to aid the\nprocess of recovery and to insure a per\nfect, all-around healing. But essentially\nthe recovery must be made by dint of\nthe working of natural forces.\nThe fact is that when we thought our\n\u25a0elves most prosperous we were least\nsecure. And the fact is also that when\nwe are least happy in a business and\neconomic way\u2014as at present\u2014we are\nmaking the most progress toward our\ngoal. Last Winter, after a heavy snow\nfall in Akron, I saw 20 or 30 boys hav\ning a perfectly'glorious time coasting on\ntheir sleds down a long hill in an out\nlying section. Enjoyment was written\non every face as the boys sped downhill.\nBut it was quite obvious that there was\nnot nearly so much joy in toiling up\nthe hill after the descent, and I have no\ndoubt that to most of the boys the hill\nseemed at least ten times as long on the\nup journey as on the trip down. I no\nticed several of the boys attempt to ride\nup the hill on the sleds which their\ncompanions were pulling. They were\npromptly put of and rolled in the snow\ndrifts along the road, of course. Prob\nably this took quite a bit of the joy of\nthe downhill coasting out of their minds.\nSome of them decided not to continue\ngoing uphill, quit and went home.\nBusiness Was Coasting.\nDuring a considerable part of the\nperiod which preceded the >tock market\ncrash of October, 1929, business was\ncoasting downhill, without those in\ncharge being aware of the fact. Busi\nness had pushed its way laboriously up\nhill after the widespread depression of\nthe years 1920 and 1921, and there was\nan irresistible tendency to \u201ctake it easy\u201d\nand coast along after the hard work of\nthe ascent.\nNearly every big business organiza\ntion\u2014and, on a proportionate scale,\n\u2022mailer ones, too\u2014added vice presidents\nand assistant superintendents and other\nassistants all along the line, to make\nthings easier for the men who had\npulled upgrade and who now wanted to\n\u201ccoast.\u201d The effort throughout busi\nness was to increase sales, without,\nhowever. Increasing the incentive to buy.\nNew factories were planned and built,\nproduction facilities increased in every\nway. without much thought of changes\nthat were inevitable in demand, sources\nof supply, in markets, in methods of\nmanufacture and distribution.\nLet me give another analogy that\nIllustrates what happened to our pros\nperity. I remember as a boy co-oper\nating with several other boys in creat\ning what we conceived would be the\nbiggest snowball ever made. When we\nfirst talked over the project one or two\nof us had in mind a snowball that\nwould tower above the tall picket fence.!\nAnother of the boys wanted to roll one\nthat would be as high as the wood\nshed: and I suppose some of the boys\nhad visions of a snowball as high as the\nhouse.\nRecalls Broken Snowball.\nWe all went to work with a will,\nrolling small snowballs and consolidat\ning them until we had one that was so\nlarge and heavy that we all had to join\nin pushing it along, to gather up a\nbroad expanse of the snow on the\nground that was getting scarcer and\nscarcer as we proceeded. We were all\nso busy pushing arid shoving without\nany definite objective or charted course\nthat we failed to note a slight declivity\nuntil our giant snowball had rolled\ndown it and disintegrated in a thou-\naand fragments when it crashed against\na tree.\nAnd that\u2019s what happened to the\nprosperity that was created in the years, j\nroughly, from 1921 to 1928. The same j\nthing has happened before. Probably j\nit will happen again.\nBut mark this: In each cycle we\ncreate a bigger snowball and by that\nI mean a greater measure of prosperity\nfor the people as a whole. And in the\ncourse of the next 10 years we shall 1\ncreate a greater prosperity than we\nhave known before, for a greater num\nber of people. We shall permanently\nlift the American standard of living to\nhigher levels than have existed before\nduring the century and a half of our\nnational life.\nIs this mere hope, or conjecture, or\nbaseless optimism?\nNot at all!\nIt is simply sound reasoning based\non experience: on knowledge of what\nhas gone before during all the decades\nsince our Government came into being, i\nI cannot predict when \u201cSteel com-!\nmon\u201d will again sell at 200 or better.!\nI do not know, and I do not care, when\nWall Street will again have a succession\nof five or six million share days on a\nrising bull market.\nI do not know when there will be a\nshortage instead of a surplus of labor\u2014\nthough I fervently hope that that will j\nbe soon.\nConditions Fundamentally Sound.\nBut I do know, with a positive con\nviction based on the indisputable facts\nof the past, that the present business\ndepression will be comparatively short\nlived in contrast with the period of na\ntional prosperity to follow. It has al\nways been so in America. It will con\ntinue to be so as long as we have what\nare commonly designated as \u201cfunda\nmentally sound\u201d conditions.\nI know that phrase has been ridden\nto death: that about the time some\nleader calls attention to \u201cthe funda\nmentally sound condition of America\u201d\nthe stock market executes another no6e\ndive and derisive comments are freely\nflung by newspaper paraeraphers at\nthose who have expressed optimism\nabout the basic business condition of\nthe country.\nNevertheless, the fact is that the\npeople of America could not possibly\navoid prosperity very long, even if they\nmade no attempt to capture it. The\ncountry possesses all the natural ele\nments that actually insure prosperity.\nWe have ample supplies of coal, of oil.\nof steel, of other useful minerals; of\ntillable, fertile soil sufficient to feed a\nmuch greater population. We have a\nclimate which favors those who want to\nwork; and we have a racial heritage\nrich in energy, initiative, enterprise,\ninvention and determination to suc\nked.\nLook back to get what might be called\na \u201cbird\u2019s-eye view\" of what these things\nhave meant in the development of\nAmerica, and instantly it becomes clear\nwhy I have no hesitancy whatever in\npredicting a greater era of prosperity\nfor our people during the next 10 years\nthan we have ever had before.\nIn the backward view we glimpse\nAmerica at the beginning, hewing homes\nout cf the wilderness, with savages to\ncombat and pestilence, drought and\ninitial poverty in money or capital to\novercome. The young Republic had to\noperate on borrowed capital; had wars\nto fight against powerful enemies: had\ninflated currency panics; had a conflict\nwithin that arrayed one section of the\ncountry against another in long, bloody\nand costly warfare: had desperate\nstruggles to maintain its truly infant\nindustries against the long-established\nmanufacturing plants of the Old World.\nDetermination and Courage Won Out.\nThese obstacles our people overcame\nby the sweat of their brow\u2019, by brain\nand by brawn, by the aid of the tre\nmendous natural resources of the coun\ntry, and by the determination and cour\nage of the people who lived within it.\nThere were cycles of prosperity and\nperiods of depression all along the road\nfrom 1776 to 1929. The \u201cdown and\nout\u201d periods came with almost monoto\nnous regularity. Men of 45 can recall\nthe depressions or panics of 1893, 1900,\n1907, 1914 and 1921. They were all\ncomparatively short lived. And after\neach there were years of better income\nand better living for the mass of our\npeople. Each wave of prosperity suc\nceeding the trough of depression in the\nsea of business activity carried us a\nlittle nearer what might be termed \"the\ngolden shore.\u201d\nWe look back over the period of na\ntional existence and see the farmers of\nanother generation afflicted with\ndroughts, grasshoppers and mortgages.\nYet steadily they forged ahead. Log\ncabins or huts dug out of dirt were\nsucceeded by well built, attractive\nhouses. The tallow candle and the oil\nlamp were displaced by electric lights.\nThe plow pulled by a mule, or even by\nchildren, gave way to a tractor moti\nvated multiple plow. Roads that were\nmere trails through a wilderness, trav\nersed by slow-moving, jolt-producing\nhorses and buggies, were succeeded by\nthe country \u201cboulevards\" of today, over\nwhich the farmer and his family speed\nin a smoothly operating automobile.\nThe farmer still has the vagaries of\nwind, weather, debt and insect pests to\ncontend with, but he has vastly more in\nmaterial comfort as the result of his\nlabor. Slowly but surely the economic\nconditions of those engaged in agricul\nture has improved. That improvement\ncan be seen with the eyes; it is not a\nmatter of statistics at all.\nCity Labor Conditions.\nSo, too, has the condition of labor In\nthe cities Improved, steadily and surely\nthrough all the years, 'good and bad.\nThere were bread and soup lines in our\nlarge cities scores of years ago. It is\nprobable those lines are shorter, pro\nportionately. now than then. They will\nbe shorter lived, at any rata; and relief\nmeasures undertaken by Government\nand private business agencies will make\nthe distress less acute now than in\ntimes past. The national conscience in\nsuch matters has grown none the less\nthan the national business structure.\nI can well remember a time, not so\nmany years ago, when the \u201cordinary\nworkingman,\" as he was then generally\ndesignated, expected none of the real\ncomforts or luxuries of life. He walked\nlong distances to work, stayed at work\n10, 12 or 14 hours under back-breaking\nhazardous conditions; walked back from\nwork to a habitation that was poorly\nlighted by lamps, with rough floors un\ncarpeted, with a tin washtub ar.d water\ndrawn from a well as the only means\nto remove the grime of toll. His family,\nof course, lacked good clothing, the\nmeans of entertainment, education or\nculture. Children went early Into the\nfactories\u2014and came out often with\nmaimed limbs or damaged bodies.\nThose conditions are now' the excep\ntion instead of the rule. Hours of work\nhave been reduced; working conditions\nhave been made less burdensome; the\nworkingman's home has hardwood floors,\nrugs, electric lights, a modern bath\nroom, a radio, an automobile for Sunday\ntrips.\nWe take these things, this general ad\nvancement, as a matter of course. We\nforget how the transformation, the prog\nress in our conditions of living came\nabout.\nIn most instances prosperity is due to\nthe fact that people realize that they\ncan make a living and that they ca\u00ab\nadvance their position in the world only\nafter they have thought out what there\nis a need for them to do and what Is\nthe best way to do it. Then they follow\nup their analysis\u2014often a subconscious\none\u2014with constant and uninterrupted\nhard work. The result is that they reap\nthe rewards of their struggles and sacri\nfices. They become prosperous, in a\nI large or moderate measure, depending\nto some extent, of course, on the in\nevitable element of chance.\nProsperity Obscures Fundamentals.\nWhen a nation becomes prosperous,\nhowever, its people tend to become self\nsatisfied and to lose sight of the funds\nmentals on which their prosperity is\nbased. The new mode of living which\nthis prosperity entails brings material\ncomforts not before enjoyed. These\ni comforts and conveniences incidental to j\nprosperity change the mental attitude\nof the people from one of striving and\naccomplishing to one of how best to i\nenjoy the luxury and wealth which they\nI now possess. Instead of \u201chustling,\u201d\nstaying with their work and maintain\ning their effort, people and I am speak\ning of those at the head as well as those\n;at the foot of industry) become more\ni and more intent upon week end excur-\nI sions to seashore and mountains. The\nnew life affords more leisure, and many\npeople heretofore hard workers become\ninactive mentally as well as physically.\nA new state of mind settles on the\npeople. They become satisfied with\nthemselves and with their position.\nThey begin to think that the prosperity\ni which they enjoy will continue despite\nthe absence of really hard work and\nsound thinking on their part. In this\nthey are wrong, and, as in every case of\nfollowing out a wrong premise, they\nmust suffer the consequences.\nIn the case of the American people\nthe consequences have been the business\ndepression which began noticeably late\nin 1929. Our people in general had as\nsumed that good business and good\nj times were here to stay and that it was\nI not necessary to safeguard their present\nI status by constant effort. The sound\nbasis of our prosperity hence began al\nmost imperceptibly to shift Its ground,\nand as this shifting gradually became\nperceptible our confidence began to\nj break down.\nA feeling of doubt settled over the\nAmerican people and this corresponded\nwith the midst of our depression. An\nuneasiness had gained ground which\nj had its reverberations in fewer sales and\nsmaller profits. There was a hesitancy\nin the market and in trade, and this\nhesitancy had become contagious. The\n(Continued on Fourth Page.)\n7\nEDITORIAL SECTION\npje Sunday fltat\nWASHINGTON, D. G, SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 2, 3930.\nWell, It\u2019s the Surplus!\nBlamed More and More for Depression\u2014Economic Expert Tells How Better Times Can Be Insured.\n\u2014Drawn for The Sunday Star by Bobert I.awson.\nBY JULIUS H. BARNES\nPresident of the National Business Survey\nConference.\nGradually the conviction\nseems to be taking root that\nthe economic nightmare that\nis troubling the dreams of\nbusiness Is the surplus. It\nmight appear in unemployment\u2014an\noverabundance of labor; In excessive\nindustrial plant capacity; in huge\nstocks of agricultural products\u2014wheat,\ncotton, sugar, coffee; In accumulated\nstores of copper, tin, rubber and silk;\nIn overproduction of oil and coal and\nInventions \u2014Boon or Curse?\nMan Made Master of Universe, But Is Not Adding to His Happiness, Declares Great Scientist.\nBY EDOUARD BELIN\nNoted French Inventor,\nAs Told to Dr. L. Aimer.\nHOW I would like to be able to be\nll\u2019ve in Mr. H G. Well's opti\nmistic visions about the future\nof humanity\u2014to feel some con\nfidence in greater happiness re\nsulting frob technical progress\u2014to dis\ncover, when I look forward, signs of\nbetterment, as Mr. Wells predicts\u2014to\nfeel satisfied that the wonders of me-\nchanical development, speed in trans\nport, wireless, television, electricity and\nmagnetism, machines that relieve man\nkind of a vast amount of tiresome and\nmonotonous work, will add to the sum\nof happiness possessed by the inhabit\nants of this globe of ours! It would\nbe pleasant to think that the man of\nthe future\u2014who will be able to tear\nround the earth at a thousand miles\nan hour, who will be able to hear and\nsee whatever goes on in the world with- i\nout going outside his house, who will\nnot have to cope with the drudgery of\ntoday\u2014will be happier than the men\nof today or yesterday.\nUnfortunately, I feel little real satis\nfaction in the progress that is being\nmade, because I cannot believe that it\nwill bring any moral benefit to man\nkind. I do not feel proud at having\nhad my small share in it, and I feel\nmore guilty than elated at the thought\nof contributing to the general and final\ndisappointment, which will be greater\nthan anything of the kind that has\never been known.\nAnything Held Possible.\nToday nothing is impossible to man.\nSome things may appear a long way\nfrom accomplishment, yet in theory\nthey cannot be ruled out. Our globe\nhas ceased to be the endless immensity\nwhich our forefathers thought it. Our\neais can catch sounds produced 10,000\nmiles away, and our eyes will soon see\nwhat happens on distant continents.\nTelevision is sure to become an every\nday fact sooner or later, and wireless\nis overcoming all resistance from the\nelements. I have not the slightest\ndoubt that our children, or perhaps our\ngrandchildren, will go about with tele\nvision cameras in their pockets. They\nwill not have to read newspapers or go\nto motion picture theaters to know\nwhat is taking place in any part of the\nearth. They will dominate the uni\nverse and Us phenomena. Nothing will\nbe beyond their reach or invisible to\nthem.\nThe trouble is that the faster they fly\nand the farther they see and hear the\nmore th-ir wants will increase. Human\ni amh't'.on knows no limit, and every\nsilver; In Idle freight cars and empty\nships that betoken a too efficient trans\nportation system. But whatever the\nguise it may assume, to it is ascribed\nthe long train of evils linked in the\nvague term\u2014depression.\nThe assurance that the world by and\nlarge is confronted with an abundance\nrather than a scarcity, that the priva\ntion and want that hovered in the wake\nof the war, when staple commodities\nwere scanty enough to be regarded as\nluxuries, have been banished might be\ntheoretically comforting, but It brings\nlittle solace to the millions of unem\nKSkSf t m\nHHIjL Wr S J n xSU.*\nI ml-\nV mi lfcwSla jpw\nAn Inventor of the Days When Science Was Young.\u2014From an old engraving\nstep forward makes it more daring,\nmore insatiable and more dissatisfied.\nIt was not very long ago that the man\nin the street shook his head incredu\nlously when he heard that certain in\nventors were reckoning on attaining a\nspeed of 100 miles an hear The same\nman now wonders why #e have not yet\nployed and other millions whose In\ncomes have been curtailed. Whether\nproduction has forged too far ahead\nor consumption has lagged too far be\nhind. the economic effect on the Indi\nvidual is equally disconoertlng.\nTo the economists consumption and\nproduction may be distinct forces. To\nthe greater part of the world\u2019s popula\ntion that must work for its living, the\none is inseparable from the other. It\nmatters little which Is the source of\nthe stagnation that overtakes business\nactivity.\nIn spite of the many Angers of\nreached 1,000 miles an hour, and, after\nhaving listened in London or Paris to\nevents taking place at Los Angeles, he\nsees nothing remarkable in being en\nabled to hear a concert ~dcast from\nsome place a couple of Hundred miles\naway.\nThe faster we move about the world,\nsuspicion pointed at the surplus\u2014a\nchangeling whose parentage is traced\nby some to the machine and mass pro\nduction\u2014its existence is very nebulous.\nStatistical delineation gives it Gargan\ntuan proportions\u2014millions of tons of\nsugar, hundreds of millions of bushels\nof wheat, millions of bales of cotton,\ncountless automobiles, vast stores of\nsilk, rubber, copper and what not.\nRarely is stress ever laid on the Gar\ngantuan world appetite that feeds on\nthis fare.\nSurplus, as a matter of fact, exists\n(Continued on Fourth Page.)\nthe' sooner we triumph over the ele\nments; the more completely we conquer\nthe outside of our sphere, the less at\ntention we pay to the inner life of our\nfellow creatures We are in such a\nhurry to cover thousands of miles that j\nwe cannot find time to attend to what\nlies nearest to us \u2014our wives, our chil- j\ndren and our friends. Family life be\ncomes less and less important to us, j\nand man becomes more and more for- 1\neign to his neighbor. I cannot help j\nthinking that to influence the minds of\nothers in the right direction is an en-;\nterprise worthy of quite as much at- j\ntention as technical progress and over\ncoming the resistance of matter. j\nOne of these days\u2014when we are able\nto photograph the mind, our feelings\nand ideas (the mental functions being\ncomposed of vibrations, this theoretic\nally is no Impossibility). when we know j\nwith scientific exactitude what is going\non in our neighbor's mind \u2014man, I fear,\nwill not use his knowledge to increase\nhappiness, to calm passions, to learn\nthe secrets of the soul and bring them\ninto harmony;, he will try to find out\nsecrets to provide himself with some\nnew instrument of warfare.\nI do not believe that the inventor is\nof very great service to his fellow\ncreatures. The public is inclined to re\ngard him as a benefactor of humanity,\nbut this is because, like a prophet, he\nhas to go on fighting for his ideas. Out\nof every 1,000 inventors. 999 are re\ngarded as lunatics, and when the\nI,oooth at last succeeds and proves the\npossibility of doing something which\nevery one else has looked upon \u25a0as im\npossible. he becomes established in the\npublic estimation as a kind of prophet.\nThis is why Edison is held in such\ngreat honor.\nInventors Use Intuition,\nAs a rule, an inventor is not a sa\nvant. The Marconi type of inventor,\nwho knows exactly what he wants, who\nstarts from a principle scientifically es\ntablished and devotes himself to elab\norating that principle, is very rare.\nMost inventors simply follow their in\ntuition, and if you ask them why they\ndid this, that or the other thing they\ncannot tell you. I am not a good en\ngineer, and yet I can sometimes solve\nproblems that are beyond the reach of\nother workers who are more highly\ntrained than myself.\nI never Imagined in my youth that I\nwould become an inventor. I was a\nstudent of philosophy and my bent of\nmind was toward questions of a gen\neral kind. In 1896. when the motion\npicture was invented by Lumlere, I had\n(Confirmed on Third Page.)\nSpecial Articles\nFOUR ELECTION RESULTS\nOF PRIMARY IMPORTANCE\nDemocratic House Might Foreshadow\nChange in President, Tariff\nand Prohibition.\nBY MARK SULLIVAN.\nFROM the varied significances of\nthe outcome of next Tuesday's\nelection four can be detached as\nhaving primary importance. One j\nis the historical significance\u2014the\nbearing that next Tuesday\u2019s result will\nhave on the presidential election two\nyears later; whether in 1932 the Re\npublicans will continue to keep control\nof the White House or will lose it to\nthe Democrats.\nThe seeond is the relation to the\ntariff; to the probability or improb\nability of another tariff revision follow\ning close on the heels of the one re\ncently completed.\nThe third is the relation of next\nTuesday's outcome to prohibition.\nThe fourth has to do with the issues i\nthat have influenced this campaign,'\nsome of them widely proclaimed but\nactually unimportant, others hardly\nmenticned but extremely fundamental.\nAs respects the historical significance\nof next Tuesday\u2019s election, if it should\nhappen that the newspapers on Wednes\nday should be called unon to announce\nDemocratic control of the Lower House,\nsuch announcement would be attended\nimmediately by predictions that in the\nnext presidential elecUion. 1932, the\nDemocrats would elect their candidate\nfor President.\nValidity of Prediction Rests on Precedent.\nThe validity of this prediction, if the\ncircumstances should cause it to be\nmade, rests wholly upon precedents.\nStated in the broadest way, the sum of\nthe precedents may be expressed thus;\nDuring the past 50 years, since 1880,\nevery time the party out of power (in j\nthe present case the Democrats I have\nwon control of the House in an elec- i\ntion coming in the middle of presi-,\ndential term, it has followed that in\nthe ensuing presidential election two\nyears subsequently the same party has*\nelected its President.\nIn detail the precedents are:\nIn 1918 the Democrats had control of\nthe presidency and of Congress <as the\nRepublicans have now). In that year\nthe Republicans won control of the\nHouse. Then two years later in the\npresidential election of 1920 the Repub\nlicans won the presidency.\nIn 1910 the Republicans were in\npower, with control of Congress and\nwith a Republican in the White House.\nIn that year and in that state of facts\nthe Democrats won control of the\nHouse. Thereafter two years later, in\n1912, the Democrats elected their can\ndidate for President.\nThese are the two most recent prece\ndents. Going on back to 1880, there\nwere four additional precedents. Upon\nthe aggregate of all these precedents\nover a period of 50 years rests the as\nsumption that if in the election next\nTuesday the Democrats should win\ncontrol of the House, they would there\nafter in 1932 elect their candidate for\nthe presidency.\nRoom for Skepticism.\nThe precedents are convincing, so far\nas precedents can convince. Actually\nthere is room for skepticism. For ex\nample, if we follow the research into\nhistory just two years further back, to\n1878, we find that the precedent falls\ndown. In that year the Democrats won\ncontrol of the House, but that did not\nprevent the Republicans, under Gar\nfield. from winning the presidential\nelection in 1880.\nAlso the one precedent upon which\nthe Democrats must rely, namely, 1910,\nis very vulnerable. Superficially and\nliterally, it is true that in 1910 the\nDemocrats won control of the House,'\nand that in 1912 they duly elected their\ncandidate for President, Woodrow Wil\nson. Upon the analogy, alleged, be\ntween 1910 and the present year, I\u00a33o,\nDemocrats depend strongly.\nThere are, however, some defects in\nthe analogy. One is that the Demo\ncrats were enabled to elect their candi- j\ndate for President in 1912 chiefly for\nthe reason that the Republican party\nwas split into two by the deepest cleav\nage that ever occurred in any American\npolitical party. The Republicans in 1912\nwere divided into the regular Republi- j\ncan party, which nominated William H.\nTaft to succeed himself, and the much\nlarger Progressive party that nominated i\nTheodore Roosevelt, \u2019lut for that split'\nin the Republicans one feels justified\nin saying the Democrats would not have\nelected their candidate for President in\n1912.\nNevertheless, if the Democrats should\nwin control of the House next Tuesday,\nthere will be deep discussion, much of\nIt Justified, about electing a Democratic,\nPresident in 1932.\nIf we turn now to the bearing of next\nTuesday\u2019s election upon the tariff, the\ncommon saying, supported by precedent\nand quite probably correct, is that if the j\nDemocrats should win control of the\nHouse on Tuesday they would proceed\nat their earliest opportunity to \"evise\nthe tariff. True, their earliest oppor-\ntunity\u201d would be considerably delayed.;\nThey would not be able to step into\ni power for 13 months\u2014in December, I\n1931. Even at that time they wouldj\nj have control of the Lower House only, j\nj They would be obliged to wait until\ni after electing their candidate for Presi\ndent (assuming they should do so) and\nuntil after his taking office in 1933.\nBut that the Democrats would in due\ncourse revise the tariff is very probable.\nOne of their outstanding leaders, ex-\nGov. James M. Cox of Ohio, their can\ndidate for President in 1920. has for- j\ni mally announced revision of the tariff\nas a consequence of Democratic victory\nnext Tuesday.\nThis idea that the Democrats, if sue- I\ncessful in carrying the Lower House on\nTuesday, would thereafter revise the\ntariff is borne out by precedent as re-\nI spects both parties. In 1918 the Repub\nlicans won control of the House, and in\n1922 they revised the tariff in he Re\npublican direction. In 1910 the Demo\ncrats won control of the House, and in i\n1913 they revised the tariff in the Dem- 1\nocratic direction. In 1894 the Republi\ncans won control of the House, and in\n1897 they revised the tariff in the Re\npublican direction. In 1890 the Demo\ncrats won control of the House, and in\n1894 they revised the tariff in the Dem\nj ocratic direction.\nProhibition Question Lacks Precedent.\nAbout the third important signifi\ncance of the outcome of next Tuesday's\nelection we have no precedent to guide\nus. The outcome will have a bearing\non prohibition. But national prohibi\ntion. unlike the tariff, is only 10 years\nold and has never before figured in a\ncongressional election or in politics at\nall in the way in which it now figures.\nAbout all that can be said is that\nduring the past few months in both\nparties the cause of repeal of the pro\nhibition amendment has made remark\nable progress. The progress has been\ngreater in the Demccratic party than in\nthe Republican.\nThe Democratic party organization\nhas gone formally and officially \"wet\u201d\nin 11 States, most of them large States\nwith large delegations in Congress and\nlarge power in national conventions for\nthe nomination of ptaeidential candi\ndates The Democratic B\u00a7rty organiza\ntion is committed to repeal of the pro\nhibition amendment or to some varia\ntion of repeal or to some sort of wet\nJ i\\ i\nprogram in New York, New Jersey,\nPennsylvania. Illinois. Connecticut, Wis\nconsin, Rhode Island. Maryland. New\nHampshire. Delaware and the State of\nWashington.\nWith so large a portion of the Demo\ncratic party, speaking in terms of geog\nraphy and population, committed to the\nwet cause, it would seem to follow that\nDemocratic victory next Tuesday would\nhave an effect of accelerating wet sen\ntiment! It would be said, whether ac\ncurately or not, that one reason for\nDemocratic victory was their favoring\nthe wet cause. To the same effect\nDemocratic leaders would feel that their\nparty fortunes had been furthered by\ngoing wet in so many States. There\nwould be. m short, a strong impulse for\nthe Democratic party to go yet farther\nand as rapidly as possible in the wet\ndirection.\nYet can we be sure? There remains\nthat Gibraltar of Democracy, the Solid\nSouth, as earnestly dry as ever. Those\nleaders now\u2019 in control of the Demo\ncratic party nationally, who have deter\nmined to take the party along the wet\nread, will encounter stiff opposition\nfrom that section of the party, the\nSouth, which in every election since the\nCivil War has provided most of the\nDemocratic electoral votes \u2014and has\ndone it dependably, practically without\ninterruption.\nIf the Democrats should next Tuesday\nelect a majority of Congress, that Con\ngress would not be wet. Par from it.\nEven the Democratic party of Congress\nwould not be wet. Assume the Demo\ncrats gain 60 seats. Assume the Demo\ncrats have in the Congress to be elected\nnext Tuesday as many as 220 seats. Out\nof that 220 fully 120 will be from the\ndry solid South or from the almost\nequally dry border States. Several more\nfrom Western and Midwestern State*\nwould be dry.\nIf it Is difficult to estimate the effect\non prohibition of a Democratic victory,\nit is even more difficult to visualize\nwhat effect, if any, on prohibition would\nensue directly from Republican victory.\nWe know the election, whichever way\nit goes, will be bound up with prohibi\ntion. In three States there are refer\nendums on it. In at least three States\ndry candidates for United States Sena\ntor are running mainly on that issue\nagainst wet candidates. Prom the elec\ntion on Tuesday deductions will be made\nabout prohibition, but it is impossible\nto outline them in advance.\nIssues Are Numerous.\nThe issues, or the conditions, or the\nmotives, or the what-nots, determining\nthe outcome of next Tuesday\u2019# election\nhave been discussed up and down the\ncountry. They have been extraordinarily\nnumerous, strangely diverse. Theoret\nically and In the true sense, this is a\nnational election having deep national\nmeaning, and having national conse\nquences of the most formidable kind.\nActually, however, this election as re\nspects the House, which Is the Impor\ntant part of it, is the aggregate of 438\nseparate elections in 435 separate con\ngressional districts, covering the entire\ncountry. More accurately, it is the ag\ngregate of about 90 separate elections,\nfor the districts which are in doubt or\nin which there are real contests \"do not\nnumber more than 90. As the aggre\ngate of 90 separate elections, the issues\nor other determining factors !h the va\nrious districts are almost as numerous\nas the districts.\nMany of the issues have dealt with\none aspect or another of prosperity. It\nis about prosperity that most of the\nspeech making and arguing has been\ndone. Through it all there has been\npractically no mention of one condition\naffecting prosperity which in the Judg\nment of some thoughtful' men is more\nprognant than any other.\nSilver and Gold Conditions Affect U. 8.\nIf the interruption to prosperity in\nthe United States had been confined to\nwhat happened within the borders of\nthe United States, we should have been\nout of the hollow and upward bound\nseveral months ago. What was ob\nserved belatedly\u2014and by many not even\nyet\u2014was that a condition in Europe and\nAsia \u2014indeed, a world-wide condition\ninvolved us in its waves. Tha condi\ntion had to do with silver and gold.\nThe price of silver went down from\nsomething like 80 cents an ounce to 30.\nThat almost destroyed the purchasing\npower of countries having silver cur\nrency in Asia and elsewhere. Along\nwith cheapness and abundance of silver\ncame a condition affecting gold. There\nhas been a decrease in the annual incre\nment of gold from mines. Drought of\ngold from mines in its immediate effect\non prices and on volume of business la\nas certain and of the same kind as re\neffect of drought of rain on crops.\nTo discuss this age-old economic phe\nnomenon is not within the scope of the\npresent article. There are many signs,\nhowever, which suggest that the. Con\ngress to be elected next Tuesday will\nbefore it ends do a good deal of talking\nabout gold and silver. True, this Is not\nnow primarily an American problem, as\nit was in the early 1890's when it pro\nvided the major part of our political\ndiscussion. As a world problem, how\never, It must affect America. Paradox\nically, it is possible it may affect us\nfavorably. In any event the writer of\nthis article has been interested to ob\nserve the reappearance in Washington\nand elsewhere of elderly gentlemen w-ho\nwish to talk about silver and gold\u2014\nmen whose early emergence into politics\ndates back to 1906 and the earlier\nof the great controversies about\nand gold.\nFast Advance Is Made\nBy Radio In Canada\nR. R. Bennett, Conservative leader,\nrecently opened his Dominion campaign\nat Winnipeg, speaking over the great\nest national radio hookup that had\never carried a political speech in that\ncountry. This, likely to be duplicated\nlater on by Premier Mackenzie King,\nLiberal chieftain, makes the present\ngeneral election the most unique in\nCanada\u2019s history. The broadcasting of\nthe speech was heard by some 423,-\n557 Canadians who secured license*\nfrom the federal authorities to have\na radio receiving set. In fact, radio\ncontinues to advance in popularity in\nCanada, the number of radios in use\nthis year being 125,000 more than last\nyear.\n\nVicar Bars Women\nIn Men\u2019s Clothing\nSt. Joseph, a church newly erected\nin Grenoble, France, a great center for\nmountain climbing, seems to have the\nfavor of tourists who come In great\nnumbers to attend mass or pray on their\nway to or from an expedition. The\nwomen naturally wear their alpinist\ncostumes, with breeches and woolen\nstockings, but the vicar of St. Joseph\nhas placed a notice in the church say\ni ing that \"Women are not allowed to\nattend holy mass in men's costumes.\u201d\nThis is rather hard on the pious lady\nmountaineers.","height":"25416","width":"19842"}}
